and brings to life the many people who were instrumental in her life: her nanny, a poor woman who raised her from a baby and whose character is conveyed through the bedtime tales she spins; her father; and her beloved grandmother, who died as a result of the political persecution she suffered.Spanning the years from 1950 to 1980, Rae Yang's story is evocative, complex, and told with striking candor. It is one of the most immediate and engaging narratives of life in post-1949 China.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aPolitical refugeeszUnited StatesxBiography. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aadolescent experience.  aanthropology.  aasia.  aasian interest.  aautobiography.  abiography.  achairman mao.  achina.  achinese cultural revolution.  achinese interest.  achinese.  acommunism.  acommunist.  acultural.  adepression.  aeast asia.  aeast asian studies.  afamily history.  afemale author.  afemale authors.  afemale leads.  ahistorical.  amaoist revolution.  amemoir.  apersonal story.  apolitical persecution.  apolitical upheaval.  apolitics.  ared guard.  arefugee memoirs.  asly humor.  asociety.  asuicide.  aturbulent years.  awomen write women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095536340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955363423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520955363/original  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO 